00:03:03.210 --> 00:03:06.310
So I guess the most
commonly known RPG

00:03:06.310 --> 00:03:08.540
is Dungeons &amp; Dragons.

00:03:08.540 --> 00:03:13.530
It's a game in which one person
creates a world with

00:03:13.530 --> 00:03:17.670
The Lord of the Rings kind of
world, and everybody plays a

00:03:17.670 --> 00:03:23.946
character in that world, Gimli
or one of the elves, or one of

00:03:23.946 --> 00:03:25.720
the hobbits.

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:28.830
And so you go around, and you
have adventures, and you do

00:03:28.830 --> 00:03:30.810
various different things that
your character is able to do,

00:03:30.810 --> 00:03:33.050
and some characters are good
at some things, and other

00:03:33.050 --> 00:03:36.010
characters are good at other
things, and you explore, and

00:03:36.010 --> 00:03:38.710
you become more powerful,
and so on, and so forth.

00:03:38.710 --> 00:03:42.260
But really what it is, it's a
shared tactical game, but it's

00:03:42.260 --> 00:03:45.420
also a shared storytelling
experience.

00:03:45.420 --> 00:03:48.030
One person comes up with the
overarching world, and

00:03:48.030 --> 00:03:51.496
everybody else figures out how
they're going to behave in

00:03:51.496 --> 00:03:53.332
that world, how they're going to
interact in that world, how

00:03:53.332 --> 00:03:56.640
they're going to make themselves
part of that world.

00:03:56.640 --> 00:04:00.230
So it's a really creative
set of games.

00:04:00.230 --> 00:04:04.170
So RPGs are not just a game,
they're a set of games.

00:04:04.170 --> 00:04:08.100
Some of them are set in our
world, in an alternate version

00:04:08.100 --> 00:04:10.070
of our world, in the future,
the past, in a

00:04:10.070 --> 00:04:12.110
galaxy far, far away.

00:04:12.110 --> 00:04:15.110
The most commonly known ones,
like Dungeons &amp; Dragons, are

00:04:15.110 --> 00:04:22.010
set in a medieval fantasy
setting, mostly pilfered from

00:04:22.010 --> 00:04:22.680
The Lord of the Rings.

00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:25.990
There are post apocalyptic ones,
and so on, and so forth.

00:04:25.990 --> 00:04:28.430
So with any world you can
imagine you mix some worlds

00:04:28.430 --> 00:04:31.430
and throw people into it, and
then you pretend that you're

00:04:31.430 --> 00:04:32.950
walking around the world.

00:04:32.950 --> 00:04:36.790
So normally what's done for
this style of game is that

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:42.040
there is a table in between the
players, or around which

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:43.660
the players gather.

00:04:43.660 --> 00:04:46.735
And sometimes there's a map,
sometimes they'll have tokens

00:04:46.735 --> 00:04:50.860
to represent yourself moving
around on the map.

00:04:50.860 --> 00:04:54.230
And almost always you'll have
dice, or in some cases cards

00:04:54.230 --> 00:04:57.960
that you draw randomly to
determine how well you succeed

00:04:57.960 --> 00:04:59.980
or fail doing something.

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:04.130
So the two main components of
a table top when you're

00:05:04.130 --> 00:05:09.030
playing are the ability to roll
dice, where everybody can

00:05:09.030 --> 00:05:11.740
see you roll the dice, so you
can't cheat, and say you got

00:05:11.740 --> 00:05:13.730
something you didn't get.

00:05:13.730 --> 00:05:17.570
And, in a lot of cases the
ability to put up a map, and

00:05:17.570 --> 00:05:19.970
then move around the map.

00:05:19.970 --> 00:05:22.520
In some cases you want to put
up pictures to give people a

00:05:22.520 --> 00:05:26.530
feeling of what they see, or
what they're interacting with.

00:05:26.530 --> 00:05:30.020
But in any case it comes down
to an image that is in a

00:05:30.020 --> 00:05:31.610
shared environment.

00:05:31.610 --> 00:05:34.380
And so that's why Hangouts
are so good for this.

00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:37.370
A lot of people have been making
virtual table tops for

00:05:37.370 --> 00:05:42.040
a lot of years, but in most of
you can't see each other, you

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:45.000
don't have that shared
videoconferencing, you have

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:49.510
some degree of sharing the same
elements, the map, or the

00:05:49.510 --> 00:05:51.010
rolling of the dice.

00:05:51.010 --> 00:05:52.590
You can text each other.

00:05:52.590 --> 00:05:55.616
But, in my opinion, and Josh
can maybe speak to this a

00:05:55.616 --> 00:05:59.040
little more, Google Hangouts
really just gives you the

00:05:59.040 --> 00:05:59.520
whole package.

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:02.160
It gives you the ability to see
everybody, as if you're

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:03.640
sitting around the same table.

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:08.010
It gives you the ability to
create a space where you can

00:06:08.010 --> 00:06:10.360
all interact with the same
elements, as if you're all

00:06:10.360 --> 00:06:13.960
rolling the same dice, or
looking at the same map.

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:17.290
So that's, I guess, the
starting of it.

