somebody wants to make a move,
you request that server,

00:12:36.910 --> 00:12:39.325
saying is this a valid move?

00:12:39.325 --> 00:12:40.610
You know, I trust you.

00:12:40.610 --> 00:12:42.990
And then you go back
and forth.

00:12:42.990 --> 00:12:46.901
So that's more secure
way of doing things.

00:12:46.901 --> 00:12:49.760
WILLIAM THOMPSON: You guys also
have, especially with the

00:12:49.760 --> 00:12:52.320
dice, you have an event
tracker there.

00:12:52.320 --> 00:12:55.980
And even if somebody goes in and
changes your shared state,

00:12:55.980 --> 00:12:57.860
each client has a record
of what's going on.

00:12:57.860 --> 00:13:00.898
So ultimately, because
transactional that way, you

00:13:00.898 --> 00:13:03.068
can walk back up the
transactions and see if

00:13:03.068 --> 00:13:03.810
somebody was cheating.

00:13:03.810 --> 00:13:08.420
CHARLES: The thing, too, is that
I wrestled with these,

00:13:08.420 --> 00:13:12.530
and I'm sure Josh has as well,
we're trying to model reality.

00:13:12.530 --> 00:13:15.676
And in reality you can put
your finger on the

00:13:15.676 --> 00:13:16.850
die and tip it over.

00:13:16.850 --> 00:13:19.020
You can put your hand up so
that people don't see what

00:13:19.020 --> 00:13:19.590
you're doing.

00:13:19.590 --> 00:13:22.360
